I try not to worry too much about that unless the situation is one where breaking mezz or not asisting will get the group killed. Before I started my chanter I'd been in groups of heavy melee pulling pairs and the chanter having a hissy fit because we tanked both. It really didn't matter in that situation, but I can understand their frustrations at not being allowed to do their jobs.<P>I made a hotkey that said "%T you're on the wrong mob please switch" and when I get broken mezzes I hit /assist and see who it is, then I hit this button. Seems to work most times. If they still don't switch I tell the group they are tanking both (or all) and most times they switch to the same target. If they refuse too, I med, saying something like "well looks like a med break for me". <P>I don't like to yell at my groupmates either so I know how you feel. I used to get really upset in the lower levels (like 15) doing orcs in Oasis, then I realized it didn't matter if we tanked 2 or I mezzed 1. So I just debuffed and let the group do its thing. Now that I'm 34 this will change some I'm sure, as breaking a mezz will start getting me killed a lot faster. When that starts happening I think I'll send private tells to my group leader and let them deal with it hehe.<P>One thing I have noticed though, is that my tanks are not shy about yelling at someone breaking mezz, or not waiting until the taunters break it first. I've been extremely lucky to have found some great tanks and if someone doesn't assist they get all over them. Many tanks take pride in breaking a mezz well and they hate to see bad assting just as much as we do. I treat these tanks well, making sure they always have haste and buffs and praise them a lot. That way they want to group with me more and I know I'm in good hands.
</FONT>
