<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Sounds like you are a bit too nice, but there's usually no need to get nasty.  Good group dynamics is all about good communication.  Sometimes the procedure is just understood when you have a group of experienced players that knows what is happening.  Other times you need to hold somebody's hand and walk them through it.  In my groups, I chat with the group after every mistake or particularly good fight.  Not in a harsh way (well usually) who was doing what and how could we (me included) do things better.  I have seen people soar in ability after a few of these sessions going from poor or mediocre players to very competent.  And, the thing is that they love me for it.  When the group starts to gel, and every fight isn't a panic situation, people start to have fun again.  A lot of people are afraid of giving advice, and some are very bad at taking it.  But, the easiest way to avoid that is to not boss people around.  Instead you involve the whole group in the assessment of what happened.  I usually lead this with an open question about what went wrong (or right.)  If you can get people to think about what they are doing and how it affects the rest of the group, you can usually get them come to the desired conclusion themselves or with a little prodding from other players.<P>That said, there are people who for whatever reasons simply won't cooperate in the group.  With these people I see little option but to kick ass and take names.
</FONT>
